          <preamble>
          </preamble>
          <tex>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.5]
  \draw[help lines] (-4, -4) grid (4, 4);
  \draw[-{Stealth[length=4pt]}, thick] (-4,0) -- (4,0);
  \draw[-{Stealth[length=4pt]}, thick] (0,-4) -- (0,4);
  % Instructor/reader can add a plotted point at (3,2) and a vector from (0,0) to (3,2)
\end{tikzpicture}
          </tex>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            The point <m>(3,2)</m> should be a dot at the location in the grid with <m>x</m>-value 3 and <m>y</m>-value 2. The vector <m>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> should be a ray with tail (or starting positing) at the origin and head (or ending positing with arrow) at the point <m>(3,2)</m>.
        </p>
    </answer>
  </example>
</page>

  <page xml:id="vector-algebra">
    <title>Vector Algebra</title>
    <p>
      When we think of an element of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> as a vector, we commonly write it as a column:
    </p>
    <me>
      \vec v \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 2\\ 3 \end{bmatrix} \in \mathbb{R}^3.
    </me>
    <p>Suppose <m>c</m> is an arbitrary real number, written <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>, and let </p>
    <me>
      \vec u \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} u_1\\ u_2 \end{bmatrix} \in \mathbb{R}^2, 
      \qquad
      \vec v \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} v_1\\ v_2 \end{bmatrix} \in \mathbb{R}^2.
    </me>
    <p>Vectors have the following properties.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <term>Scalar Multiple:</term>
        <me>c\,\vec u \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} c\,u_1\\ c\,u_2 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
      </li>
      <li>
        <term>Vector Addition:</term>
        <me>
          \vec u + \vec v 
          \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} u_1\\ u_2 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} v_1\\ v_2 \end{bmatrix}
          \;=\; \begin{bmatrix} u_1 + v_1\\ u_2 + v_2 \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p >
      Vectors in higher dimensions satisfy the same operations componentwise.
    </p>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Some examples:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Let <m>\vec u = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>c = 2</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Then <m>c\vec u = 2\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2(1) \\ 2(3) \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If <m>d = -1</m>, then <m>d\vec u = -1\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Geometrically, multiplying by the scalar <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m> scales the vector by <m>|c|</m> and rotates the vector about the origin by 180 degrees if <m> c &lt; 0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Let <m>\vec u = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec v = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Then <m>\vec u + \vec v = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 - 2 \\ 2 + 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Geometrically, vector addition follows the parallelogram rule. This means that to sketch the vector <m> \vec u + \vec v</m>, you first sketch the vector <m>\vec u</m> starting from the origin. Then, you sketch the vector <m>\vec v</m> starting from the head of <m>\vec u</m>. The vector <m>\vec u + \vec v</m> is the drawn by starting at the origin and ending where <m>\vec v</m> ended.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Vectors with a different number of entries cannot be added together.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> is not defined.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </solution>

  </page>

  <page xml:id="lin-comb-span">
    <title>Linear Combinations and Span</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-linear-combination-span" workspace="0.5in">
      <statement>
        <ol>
          <li>
            Given vectors <m>\vec v_1,\vec v_2,\dotsc,\vec v_p \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> and scalars <m>c_1,c_2,\dotsc,c_p</m>, 
            the vector
            <me>
              \vec y \;=\; c_1 \vec v_1 + c_2 \vec v_2 + \cdots + c_p \vec v_p
            </me>
            is called a <term>linear combination</term> of <m>\vec v_1,\dotsc,\vec v_p</m> with weights <m>c_1,\dotsc,c_p</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The set of all linear combinations of <m>\vec v_1,\dotsc,\vec v_p</m> is called the <term>span</term> of these vectors.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Any two vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> that are not scalar multiples of one another span <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>. 
      Thus, any vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> can be written as a linear combination of such a pair.
    </p>

